##Huanggang, Hubei: A family of four suspected cases difficult to confirm

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

If my dad really doesn't make it, because without a diagnosis, he'll end up as a "probable case, " and we won't know for sure if it's the COVID-19.

Dictation | Feng Hong
Intern reporter | Yue Ying Reporter | Wang Shan

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Dictation | Feng Hong

Intern reporter | Yue Ying Reporter | Wang Shan

My family is in Huanggang, Hubei Province. There are four people in my family. My parents, my brother and I are all suspected cases. Both of my father's lungs were infected, the doctor said the lungs are white, according to the CT images, basically can be identified as new pneumonia, but the hospital did not have reagent boxes, do not have the conditions, so the diagnosis is "suspected. ". We've signed two death notices since the infection. My mother's condition was slightly less severe, but she was also quarantined in the hospital. My brother and I were doing better, so we were placed in a home quarantine.

I've been thinking about it for a long time, and I don't know how my family got infected. My parents are both 50 years old, my father had been in the hospital once before, my mother has diabetes, but the overall health is OK. In retrospect, the situation may have occurred on January 7, when my parents and I drove to Wuhan to pick up my brother from college for the holidays. My parents and I went to a mall in the morning, less than two kilometers away from the south China seafood market, because it was almost new year, crowded people, and then we left. We had no idea that there was a new type of pneumonia in Wuhan, nor did we see masks on the streets or in shopping malls. After that, we went to a market before we went to Wuchang to pick up my brother. After a day or two of return, my father began coughing, fever, all over weakness, unable to eat rice, after four or five days, breathing becomes difficult.

Everyone thought he just had the common cold, but as it got worse, we went to the local hospital to get an X-ray and an infusion. The family thought he might have a run-of-the-mill case of pneumonia and were nervous. The doctors at the hospital did not connect his illness to the new type of pneumonia and treated him as normal. A few days of fluids, and my dad's getting worse. I thought maybe the medical conditions weren't good enough, so on January 19 I took him to the top three hospitals in Huanggang, the Central Huanggang Hospital, to be examined. The results came out the same day. Huanggang Central said the condition required hospitalization and immediate transfer to the ICU, so they sent an ambulance to pick him up. But on the way to the hospital, they got a phone call and said they couldn't take him, so we had to take him home.

That day we examined my mother, who had the same symptoms three or four days after my father's symptoms appeared, but to a lesser degree. It turns out my mom was infected, too. My brother and I had few symptoms at the time, and I felt healthy, but the doctor said that since we were both in close contact with our parents, we had to be screened. After the examination, we were also classified as suspected cases. I'm married and haven't lived with my parents since I came back from Wuhan, so the situation is the least serious. My brother takes my dad to get shots every day. He's worse off than me.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
After that, we went to Tongji Huangzhou Hospital, which refused admission. We also asked the Huanggang Hospital of Traditional Chinese Medicine, still do not accept, their argument is only to wait for the health commission to send word can be admitted. There were only a few good hospitals in Huanggang, and we had no choice but to keep pleading with them. Finally, a very kind deputy dean himself made the position, said, "I accept this patient. " My parents this just admitted to the hospital. After I was admitted to Huanggang City Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine, I learned that it was not that the hospital did not want to admit patients, but that they really did not have beds. The hospital, which had no respiratory infection department, had been set up on an ad hoc basis, with floors set aside for patients and doctors transferred on an ad hoc basis.

My Dad's in a standard isolation ward. I can understand why medical resources are so scarce right now. But I told the doctor that if my dad was in critical condition, he had to be transferred to the ICU, and the doctor promised. It's been five days since January 20th since my parents were hospitalized. Mom has some relief, but dad is more and more serious, breathing is very difficult, eating and urinating can not take care of themselves, are the mother in the care. I feel bad that if my dad doesn't make it, because without a diagnosis, he'll end up as a "probable case, " and we won't know for sure if it's the COVID-19. Last night, I suddenly received a phone call from my mother, said she was transferred to another hospital, the facilities are very poor. The exact reason for the transfer, she doesn't know.

After mom was transferred to the hospital, it was a big problem who would take care of Dad. The emts at the hospital were so busy, no one could take care of him, only the family, so my brother was going to go. "Can the accompanying family wear the same protective clothing as the doctor? " He asked. "No. " He asked. "Will it cross-infect again? " The doctor told us in frustration, "The hospital is understaffed, if you want to accompany, do not be afraid of infection, otherwise do not accompany. " But if we do not take care of Dad, who can take care of him?

Since mom was moved, Dad has stopped eating in order to reduce the number of times he has to go to the bathroom. My brother and I are home alone. We stayed at home as much as possible, except for the necessary travel and medicine. My father is a very popular man. Many people call him. But I tried to talk him out of it, and Dad's wearing an oxygen mask, so it's hard to talk. In fact, the doctor also said that I need more rest, but I am now overwhelmed every day, contact with the hospital, contact with the government, contact with various relatives. Ever since I found out that my father had this disease, I've been so nervous every day, and every time I sign a death warrant, the stress just gets worse.

I now go to the pharmacy every day to buy immunoglobulins, which doctors tell us are useful and can boost immunity. The whole family needs it. It's over $10,000. They don't have it at the hospital, and it's hard to get it at the pharmacy, and sometimes I have to go to a couple of places to get it. This kind of protein, the drugstore said to buy a lot of people, 560 a bottle, the next day I went up to 720 a bottle, now 560 is not available. The immunoglobulins are taken to the hospital, where they are written with the patient's name and bed number and injected.

Until January 19th, few people on Huanggang Street wore masks, then more and more, and now almost all wear them. The relatives of patients in the hospital did not communicate with each other, we are afraid of cross-infection. And the doctors are getting more protective. When we first went to the hospital, the doctors only wore masks. Now they use protective clothing and goggles. My brother and I plan to observe the situation at home, if there has been no fever and cough, we will go to the hospital for follow-up. I don't know. Does this mean we're cured? Actually, we don't know. One day when we were having injections, a man came over to have this protein injected. He didn't have an infection, he just wanted to prevent it.

In addition to the protein injections, my brother and I had been prescribed Oseltamivir, but I had just tweeted that it wasn't working for the new pneumonia. So where does that leave me and my brother? What else can we do but inject the protein to boost the immune system? I feel so powerless.

Medical staff wearing protective clothing for treatment (photo provided by China News Service)

There have been 12 confirmed cases in Huanggang, and I haven't tried to contact them. Doctors say there's no kit. How did they diagnose it? I don't know. Every day, in addition to dealing with my family, I have been reading about the outbreak on Weibo. Now many people on the Internet are afraid of Wuhan. Will this report make people afraid of Huanggang again? I'd love to transfer my dad to a better hospital, but right now the policy is "local discovery, local treatment. ". I trust the government. I trust the hospital.

(Feng Hong is a pseudonym)
